{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"98bf0d0c-0e5d-41de-aaad-5c9aec22fc35","content":"When `UseLegacyV2RuntimeActivationPolicy` is set to `true` (1), it changes how the CLR handles mixed-mode assemblies (those containing both managed and native code) built against .NET Framework 2.0/3.5.\n\n**What it does:**\n- Binds legacy COM-activated managed components to the **current runtime** (e.g., CLR 4.0) instead of the runtime they were built against (CLR 2.0).\n- Mimics .NET 2.0's \"greedy\" activation behavior where the first runtime loaded handles all activation requests.\n\n**How it affects runtime selection:**\n- **Without it:** CLR 4.0 refuses to load mixed-mode assemblies compiled for CLR 2.0, throwing a `FileLoadException`.\n- **With it:** CLR 4.0 loads those assemblies in-process, applying its own runtime policies.\n\n**Where it's configured:**\n```xml\n<!-- In app.config or web.config -->\n<configuration>\n  <startup useLegacyV2RuntimeActivationPolicy=\"true\">\n    <supportedRuntime version=\"v4.0\" />\n  </startup>\n</configuration>\n```\n\n**Key considerations:**\n- It's a compatibility shim — ideally you'd recompile the assembly targeting CLR 4.0.\n- It applies process-wide, affecting all COM activation in that process.\n- It has no effect in .NET Core/.NET 5+, which use a completely different activation model.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"dfa54f2f-55c1-49b6-a70c-965a373ad519","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about CLR (Common Language Runtime) activation logging, specifically about the `UseLegacyV2RuntimeActivationPolicy` setting. This is a .NET Framework concept related to how the runtime is selected and activated. Let me answer this from my knowledge.","outputTokens":426},"id":"4486a91f-9cf8-48d1-b25e-9df2bf0dfe2c","timestamp":"2026-04-05T01:13:09.542Z","parentId":"e9de8c42-1d14-468d-9253-cb64f1f99a7d"}
